Echoing a character to /proc/sysrq trigger can be used to crash, sync
filesytems, reboot, halt the OS, or print debugging information to /dev/console:

# echo " " > /proc/sysrq-trigger : show all available triggers and their keys
SysRq : HELP : loglevel(0-9) reboot(b) crash(c) terminate-all-tasks(e) memory-full-oom-kill(f) kill-all-tasks(i) thaw-filesystems(j) sak(k) show-backtrace-all-active-cpus(l) show-memory-usage(m) nice-all-RT-tasks(n) poweroff(o) show-registers(p) show-all-timers(q) unraw(r) sync(s) show-task-states(t) unmount(u) force-fb(V) show-blocked-tasks(w) dump-ftrace-buffer(z)

# echo c > /proc/sysrq-trigger : force crash
# echo s > /proc/sysrq-trigger : sync filesystems
# echo b > /proc/sysrq-trigger : reboot without syncing
# echo o > /proc/sysrq-trigger : poweroff without syncing

Note: The stack trace generated by the "l" trigger logs its output to the
kernel log and can be viewed with dmesg.
